62
00:02:32,368 --> 00:02:37,368
== sync, corrected by <font color=#00FF00>elderman</font> ==
<font color=#00FFFF>@elder_man</font>

63
00:02:37,819 --> 00:02:39,386
Are you crazy?

64
00:02:39,388 --> 00:02:40,437
You don't want

65
00:02:40,439 --> 00:02:42,306
your girlfriend
at work with you.

66
00:02:42,308 --> 00:02:45,008
Hell Clam.

67
00:02:45,010 --> 00:02:46,527
Why not?

68
00:02:46,529 --> 00:02:49,113
Hairy Fairy.

69
00:02:49,115 --> 00:02:50,681
I think it could be romantic.

70
00:02:50,683 --> 00:02:52,650
You know, my parents met
at his place of work.

71
00:02:52,652 --> 00:02:55,686
Your father's a gynecologist.

72
00:02:55,688 --> 00:02:56,870
I know.

73
00:02:56,872 --> 00:02:59,823
What started as a pap smear
turned into a date.

74
00:03:01,293 --> 00:03:02,676
Which turned
into her working there,

75
00:03:02,678 --> 00:03:04,645
which turned into marriage,
which then turned into hatred,

76
00:03:04,647 --> 00:03:07,197
which continues to this day.

77
00:03:07,299 --> 00:03:10,067
Two-Eyed Cyclops.

78
00:03:10,069 --> 00:03:12,903
Would you please tell him
this isn't a good idea?

79
00:03:12,905 --> 00:03:14,271
No, no, I think it'll be great.

80
00:03:14,273 --> 00:03:15,889
Maybe next time he gets
conjunctivitis at work,

81
00:03:15,891 --> 00:03:19,943
she can hold his head and try
to put the drops in his eyes.

82
00:03:19,945 --> 00:03:22,429
Giant baby.

83
00:03:22,431 --> 00:03:24,281
That's a Raging Ogre.

84
00:03:24,283 --> 00:03:26,517
Yeah, I know.

85
00:03:28,520 --> 00:03:30,687
I'm just saying, I'd never want
to work with Bernadette.

86
00:03:30,689 --> 00:03:32,656
Can you imagine seeing
someone all day long

87
00:03:32,658 --> 00:03:34,124
and then you're
supposed to hang out

88
00:03:34,126 --> 00:03:35,826
with them after work, too?

89
00:03:35,828 --> 00:03:37,494
Hold on. We do
that all the time.

90
00:03:37,496 --> 00:03:39,229
You and I work together
and play together.

91
00:03:39,231 --> 00:03:42,883
Yeah, I know, and it drove me
into the arms of another woman.

92
00:03:44,702 --> 00:03:46,720
Bipolar Bear.

93
00:03:46,722 --> 00:03:49,606
Well, I appreciate your concern,

94
00:03:49,608 --> 00:03:52,810
but I won't be seeing any more
of Amy than I already do.

95
00:03:52,812 --> 00:03:55,095
I assume we'll deduct
any extra time we spend together

96
00:03:55,097 --> 00:03:57,965
at work from our weekly quota.

97
00:03:59,884 --> 00:04:02,553
Please let me be there
when you tell her that.

98
00:04:03,521 --> 00:04:05,689
Why? So you can see the
look on Amy's face

99
00:04:05,691 --> 00:04:07,991
when she hears
my top-notch idea?

100
00:04:07,993 --> 00:04:10,577
Please, oh, please,
just let me be there.

101
00:04:12,547 --> 00:04:15,682
So, Amy, what are you gonna
be working on at Caltech?

102
00:04:15,684 --> 00:04:17,468
I'm leading a study to see

103
00:04:17,470 --> 00:04:19,369
if deficiency of the
monoamine oxidase enzyme

104
00:04:19,371 --> 00:04:21,445
leads to paralyzing
fear in monkeys.

105
00:04:21,470 --> 00:04:22,340
Oh.

106
00:04:22,341 --> 00:04:25,159
If they're anything like humans,
the answer's yes.

107
00:04:25,161 --> 00:04:27,578
Wait, you've-you've done
this experiment on humans?

108
00:04:27,580 --> 00:04:30,264
You mean like death row inmates
with nothing to lose?

109
00:04:30,366 --> 00:04:33,083
No, that would be unethical.

110
00:04:34,619 --> 00:04:36,587
You know,
not a lot of people know this,

111
00:04:36,589 --> 00:04:37,838
but the monoamine oxidase enzyme

112
00:04:37,840 --> 00:04:39,790
was discovered by a woman,
Mary Bernheim.

113
00:04:42,277 --> 00:04:43,543
That's right.

114
00:04:43,545 --> 00:04:46,546
My phone is just
as smart as you guys.

115
00:04:48,317 --> 00:04:49,449
Amy, Bernadette, Penny.

116
00:04:49,451 --> 00:04:51,151
Amy, Bernadette,
Penny.

117
00:04:51,153 --> 00:04:53,537
Amy, Bernadette, Penny.

118
00:04:53,539 --> 00:04:56,306
He's never gonna
stop doing that, is he?

119
00:04:56,308 --> 00:04:57,441
I don't mind.

120
00:04:57,443 --> 00:04:59,109
I'm hoping to put
his love of repetition

121
00:04:59,111 --> 00:05:00,861
to good use someday.

122
00:05:03,247 --> 00:05:05,232
Hi. Um...

123
00:05:05,234 --> 00:05:06,400
I've reconsidered.

124
00:05:06,402 --> 00:05:07,901
Uh, you can't work
where I work.

125
00:05:07,903 --> 00:05:09,269
Enjoy the rest
of your evening.

126
00:05:09,271 --> 00:05:10,904
Sheldon.

127
00:05:10,906 --> 00:05:13,123
I-I already signed
the contract.

128
00:05:13,125 --> 00:05:14,524
I cashed a check.

129
00:05:14,526 --> 00:05:16,576
Mmm... you are not going

130
00:05:16,578 --> 00:05:18,428
to come out of
this looking good.

131
00:05:18,430 --> 00:05:19,663
Sheldon,
I don't understand.

132
00:05:19,665 --> 00:05:21,581
I thought you said
you were fine with it.

133
00:05:21,583 --> 00:05:22,699
Well, I was.

134
00:05:22,701 --> 00:05:24,334
But that was before
Howard explained to me

135
00:05:24,336 --> 00:05:26,470
how awful it would be
if he had to work

136
00:05:26,472 --> 00:05:28,138
with his significant other.

137
00:05:28,140 --> 00:05:30,724
He said what?

138
00:05:30,726 --> 00:05:32,676
Now, don't be insulted.

139
00:05:32,678 --> 00:05:36,897
He just thinks too much of you
would be mind-numbingly tedious.

140
00:05:36,899 --> 00:05:40,067
Excuse me, I need to have
a chat with my husband.

141
00:05:40,069 --> 00:05:41,902
Yeah, well, now,
well... keep it short.

142
00:05:41,904 --> 00:05:45,439
Fr-From what I gather,
brevity is your friend.

143
00:05:46,574 --> 00:05:48,742
So, are we good here?

144
00:05:48,744 --> 00:05:50,327
No, we're not good here.

145
00:05:50,329 --> 00:05:51,828
I am working on this project.

146
00:05:51,830 --> 00:05:54,081
Yeah, and you can't tell her
what she can and cannot do.

147
00:05:54,083 --> 00:05:56,099
Last week, you told Leonard
he couldn't wear

148
00:05:56,101 --> 00:05:58,301
his Wookiee jacket
out in public.

149
00:05:58,303 --> 00:05:59,519
That's different.

150
00:05:59,521 --> 00:06:01,455
I'm not going to the mall
with someone dressed

151
00:06:01,457 --> 00:06:03,540
dumb space bear.

152
00:06:05,576 --> 00:06:07,627
Sheldon, you don't have to worry
about me bothering you.

153
00:06:07,629 --> 00:06:08,879
I'll be in a different building.

154
00:06:08,881 --> 00:06:10,747
And we don't even have
to have lunch together.

155
00:06:10,749 --> 00:06:11,865
Really?

156
00:06:11,867 --> 00:06:14,518
Yes. Before all things,
I'm a scientist.

157
00:06:14,520 --> 00:06:16,970
I'm just there to do my work
and, with a little luck,

158
00:06:16,972 --> 00:06:19,606
scare the living crap
out of some monkeys.

159
00:06:19,608 --> 00:06:23,143
Hmm.

160
00:06:23,145 --> 00:06:25,812
You sure your mothlike
personality won't be drawn

161
00:06:25,814 --> 00:06:28,565
to this blazing fire
that is myself?

162
00:06:31,536 --> 00:06:33,787
More and more sure.

163
00:06:33,789 --> 00:06:36,873
Well, then, you
have my permission.

164
00:06:36,875 --> 00:06:37,958
I didn't ask
for your permission.

165
00:06:37,960 --> 00:06:39,159
Too late. No backsies.

166
00:06:41,612 --> 00:06:44,414
No, no, listen to me.
Sheldon misunderstood.

167
00:06:44,416 --> 00:06:45,382
What I meant was,

168
00:06:45,384 --> 00:06:46,449
if we worked together,

169
00:06:46,451 --> 00:06:48,118
there'd be too much
of me for you,

170
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:50,253
not the other way around.

171
00:06:50,255 --> 00:06:52,723
Howard, if you're going
to lie to your wife,

172
00:06:52,725 --> 00:06:55,325
don't start the sentence
with "Sheldon misunderstood."

173
00:06:56,878 --> 00:06:58,011
That's a dead giveaway.

174
00:06:58,013 --> 00:06:59,930
Well?

175
00:06:59,932 --> 00:07:01,131
Okay, fine.

176
00:07:01,133 --> 00:07:02,899
I did say that,
and I think it's true.

177
00:07:02,901 --> 00:07:05,018
I think if we worked together
and lived together,

178
00:07:05,020 --> 00:07:06,520
we'd get sick of each other.

179
00:07:06,522 --> 00:07:08,105
Yeah, but to be fair,
he only said the part

180
00:07:08,107 --> 00:07:09,189
about him
getting sick of you.

181
00:07:09,191 --> 00:07:11,024
For the love of God, why?!

182
00:07:15,213 --> 00:07:17,864
What exactly do you
think you'd get sick of?

183
00:07:17,866 --> 00:07:20,016
His only options here
are to fake a heart attack

184
00:07:20,018 --> 00:07:22,385
or have a real one.

185
00:07:22,387 --> 00:07:25,655
It-it's nothing
in particular. I...

186
00:07:25,657 --> 00:07:27,824
Is it my voice?
Am I too bossy?

187
00:07:27,826 --> 00:07:28,959
What...?

188
00:07:28,961 --> 00:07:31,878
My arm is feeling numb.

189
00:07:32,797 --> 00:07:35,782
Nailed it.

190
00:07:35,784 --> 00:07:39,386
That's the wrong arm for
a heart attack, doofus.

191
00:07:41,222 --> 00:07:44,357
My point is, I'm sure
there are things about me

192
00:07:44,359 --> 00:07:46,643
that would drive you crazy
if you had to deal

193
00:07:46,645 --> 00:07:48,395
with them all day long.

194
00:07:48,397 --> 00:07:50,597
Like looking me in the
eye and lying to me?

195
00:07:50,599 --> 00:07:52,149
Oh, well, come on, I just...

196
00:07:52,151 --> 00:07:55,402
Where am I supposed to
look when I lie to you?

197
00:07:55,404 --> 00:07:57,754
Find somewhere else
to sleep tonight.

198
00:07:57,756 --> 00:07:59,906
Oh, Bernie...

199
00:08:06,864 --> 00:08:10,467
If it makes you feel any better,
Amy and I are fine.

200
00:08:13,070 --> 00:08:15,238
I mean, really good.

201
00:08:17,475 --> 00:08:19,843
So, boys, how was
the pajama party?

202
00:08:19,845 --> 00:08:23,730
You guys jump on the bed
and sing into hair brushes?

203
00:08:23,732 --> 00:08:25,932
It wasn't a pajama party.

204
00:08:25,934 --> 00:08:28,435
It was just a couple of bros
hanging out, giggling,

205
00:08:28,437 --> 00:08:31,521
eating cookie dough
and watching <i>Princess Bride.</i>

206
00:08:33,074 --> 00:08:34,608
Please, stop talking.

207
00:08:36,244 --> 00:08:38,862
As you wish.

208
00:08:42,667 --> 00:08:44,734
I mean, you know, Sheldon,
none of this would've happened

209
00:08:44,736 --> 00:08:46,203
if I hadn't tried
to help you.

210
00:08:46,205 --> 00:08:48,788
Uh, it also wouldn't
have happened

211
00:08:48,790 --> 00:08:50,290
if, in the early universe,

212
00:08:50,292 --> 00:08:53,793
hydrogen was a little more
common or a little less common.

213
00:08:53,795 --> 00:08:56,279
This is fun. Your turn.

214
00:08:57,265 --> 00:08:58,598
Gentlemen.
Hey, Amy.

215
00:08:58,600 --> 00:09:00,283
Hello.

216
00:09:00,285 --> 00:09:01,685
That was kind of icy.

217
00:09:01,687 --> 00:09:03,336
You two okay?

218
00:09:03,338 --> 00:09:04,354
Oh, we're fine.

219
00:09:04,356 --> 00:09:05,772
As Howard advised,

220
00:09:05,774 --> 00:09:07,974
she's merely respecting our
professional boundaries.

221
00:09:07,976 --> 00:09:08,942
Smart.

222
00:09:08,944 --> 00:09:10,544
Take relationship advice
from a man

223
00:09:10,546 --> 00:09:12,963
who spent last night
braiding Raj's hair.

224
00:09:15,432 --> 00:09:18,451
Yeah, you make
a good point.

225
00:09:18,453 --> 00:09:20,654
It would appear
I was worried for nothing.

226
00:09:20,656 --> 00:09:22,205
Look at her, desperately wishing

227
00:09:22,207 --> 00:09:24,157
she was over here
at the cool table.

228
00:09:26,577 --> 00:09:28,328
Don't worry, little moth.

229
00:09:28,330 --> 00:09:30,630
The flame will come to you.

230
00:09:32,833 --> 00:09:34,568
Oh, uh...

231
00:09:34,570 --> 00:09:36,386
on the off chance that
Bernadette doesn't call back

232
00:09:36,388 --> 00:09:37,771
and apologize,
how do you feel

233
00:09:37,773 --> 00:09:39,673
about Mexican food
for dinner tonight?

234
00:09:39,675 --> 00:09:41,841
I-I don't know.
Sounds kind of heavy.

235
00:09:41,843 --> 00:09:44,811
That's 'cause you always
fill up on chips.

236
00:09:44,813 --> 00:09:47,480
And this is Dr. Gunderson
from Stockholm.

237
00:09:47,482 --> 00:09:49,032
Ah, Sweden.

238
00:09:49,034 --> 00:09:50,734
Yeah, home of my favorite Muppet

239
00:09:50,736 --> 00:09:53,720
and, uh,
second favorite meatball.

240
00:09:57,141 --> 00:10:01,344
Okay, the Nordic reputation for
lack of humor is well-founded.

241
00:10:02,813 --> 00:10:05,582
Boy, is his name Gunderson
or No-Funderson?

242
00:10:06,834 --> 00:10:09,069
Where are we going
with this, Dr. Cooper?

243
00:10:09,071 --> 00:10:11,104
Oh, please, I'm your boyfriend.

244
00:10:11,106 --> 00:10:13,556
You call me Sheldon.

245
00:10:13,558 --> 00:10:16,159
That's right,
I am in a boy-girl relationship

246
00:10:16,161 --> 00:10:18,929
with this cute little
lump of wool.

247
00:10:18,931 --> 00:10:20,046
Sheldon...

248
00:10:20,048 --> 00:10:21,765
It's a physical
relationship, too.

249
00:10:21,767 --> 00:10:25,518
Hand-holding, hugging...
even on hot days.

250
00:10:25,520 --> 00:10:27,387
Ow.

251
00:10:28,172 --> 00:10:29,539
Okay, here's a new one.

252
00:10:29,541 --> 00:10:31,141
Apparently now
we kick each other

253
00:10:31,143 --> 00:10:32,776
in the shin under the table.

254
00:10:34,478 --> 00:10:37,013
How do you like it
when I do it to you?

